  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I see the saved Wi-Fi passwords on my mobile?",
  "response": "Viewing saved Wi-Fi passwords on your mobile device can vary depending on the operating system you are using. Here are the general steps for both Android and iOS devices:\n\n### Android\n\nOn Android devices, the process may vary depending on the version of Android and the manufacturer of the device. Here are the steps for recent versions of Android (10 and above):\n\n1. **Open Settings**: Go to the Settings app on your device.\n2. **Network & Internet**: Tap on \"Network & Internet\" or \"Connections\" depending on your device.\n3. **Wi-Fi**: Select \"Wi-Fi.\"\n4. **Saved Networks**: Select \"Saved networks\" or \"Manage networks.\"\n5. **Select a Network**: Tap on the network for which you want to see the password.\n6. **Share Network**: Tap the \"Share\" button. You may need to authenticate using your fingerprint, PIN, or password.\n7. **QR Code**: A QR code will appear with the network's information, including the password.\n\nNote: If you are using a device with Android 9 or older, you may need to use third-party apps or root your device to see saved Wi-Fi passwords.\n\n### iOS\n\nOn iOS devices, directly viewing saved Wi-Fi passwords is not typical without additional steps, but you can find them through your Mac if they are synced via iCloud Keychain:\n\n**Using iCloud Keychain on a Mac:**\n1. **System Preferences**: Open \"System Preferences\" on your Mac.\n2. **iCloud**: Select \"iCloud\" and ensure \"Keychain\" is turned on.\n3. **Keychain Access**: Open \"Keychain Access\" from the Applications > Utilities folder.\n4. **Search for the Network**: Use the search bar to find the Wi-Fi network you're interested in.\n5. **Double-click the Network**: Double-click the network entry.\n6. **Show Password**: Check the \"Show password\" box. You may need to enter your Mac's administrator password to reveal it.\n\nIf you need to view the password directly on an iPhone or iPad, you might use a workaround involving Mac synchronization, as directly accessing Wi-Fi passwords on the device itself is generally restricted for security reasons.\n\nPlease remember that you should only view or share passwords for networks you have permission to access.",
